“The timing for the rescue operation in the U.S. is uncertain and will affect the financial markets worldwide,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft support for the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the burglary.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (almost 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>) should be spent.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would regulate the fundamental causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the largest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by nearly 7%, with a similar decline last seen in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any indications that the draft would not come through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress Makes Concession: US Government May Pump $700 Billion into Banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement on financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. legislators made a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion grant to the U.S. financial system (approximately 12 trillion kroner).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final draft of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services Barney Frank told Reuters agency.
In the Senate, according to various figures, the plan could probably be voted on at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first significant psychological factor for a revitalization of the financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to them, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for a purchase of unavailable mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're on target," Paulson said.
A Signal for Asia Businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a definitive agreement in Congress before Sunday.
It aims to calm investors from doing business on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether the negotiations at the last minute could still fail at a problem.
Legislators hope it will be passed in the next few days.
However, the law will still undergo some changes.
The total amount of aid to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the rest of the money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush sees progress in negotiations as positive
