The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the programme and to set up a committee to oversee the fund.
This should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it purchases, with the goal of lowering the monthly costs for the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"And that's because you don't know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial to how the financial sector and the government divide the losses among themselves,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive, according to Marek.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and that they adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement about a passing is the most important thing at this moment," Marek emphasized.
Duel on Messers Schneide: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost any mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls yet.
So, of course, it is better to just buy a phone.
Despite all this, there are plenty of reasons why you should get a stand-alone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s hard to buy a great, expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for them.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
This is also the case with music on travel, i.e. with compressed music, expressed in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a pink-floyd fan will probably hardly use headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is broad.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what cell phones can do, they don’t even make sense.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, the phone and the Simsen, it can play music and videos, record both, it sometimes has a better, sometimes a worse camera and may also be able to navigate.
And if you still include the smart phones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for longer than ten to twelve hours, usually it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should count on the cheap phones that they can’t play music for more than a few hours.
If you still make phone calls from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones will last at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation at once.
Another problem is if you want to transfer the music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices has a USB port, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can cope with the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
For players, except for exceptions (iPod), you do not need special software.
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user rating.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and the type of sound and, of course, the ease of use.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you listen to it only briefly every day, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which almost every cell phone can do.
You also do not have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 create all, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is among the most widely used, and moreover, most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via the mobile internet, and you can buy a song or album.
This service can in and of itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is usually limited to fast radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can access the built-in speaker that almost every cell phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you already get a very decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players in turn lies in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile internet and a subsequently horrendous bill for data transmissions.
Which device should you use now
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But be careful.
Basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you prefer to take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have stand-alone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The widest here is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand kroner, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours maximum) provide you with MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe it won't be long.
That the Czech mobile operators work among the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
Incidentally, this was confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps taken by the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely – for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to grumble about the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
In addition, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has very many chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
However, there is one more option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market that led to a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile phone providers then also had to react to.
Before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn’t take long to look for examples.
In February this year we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not require a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, which, however, is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
Tesco Mobile, for example, offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to target a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"True guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>’s spokesperson said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, press officer for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Your interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the corporate customer segment.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecom services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we were already able to achieve negotiation progress," said Pavel Kaidl, the group's press spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject with a complex and reputable project in this area has addressed us," says his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2.
Other providers also point out the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> rarely agrees with O2's statement: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
She added: “By the end of the year, hardly any virtual provider will appear on T-Mobile’s network.
At this moment, we would already have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in such a short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we regard as the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also a decline in profits.
So why should it be easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> came from T-Mobile at the time U:fon was launched.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
In view of this approach, however, mobile operators are surprised by the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other advanced countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, referred to this whole issue as its very typical attitude.
“The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider about the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Department in his response to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
This is more than worrying from an authority that is supposed to represent consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position in the market.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Across the country, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
But probably the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are not among the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way whatsoever.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their trading in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many disputes.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, after which telecommunications from the perspective of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators hold a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for his network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a particular segment.
But even if you don’t agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile service providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS only need to know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It is possible when no one is looking
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Our own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic business customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"Should there be cases that you describe, then it can be a breach of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not go around among the responsible persons of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, the activities of these companies are not to be neglected, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile service providers.”
But at least that would have to be strange.
In addition, another question arises for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Before such a procedure, mobile operators close their eyes, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competencies to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration by the providers that they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their creation virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which in no way sought to protect the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competencies in these cases is more than favorable.
But let’s not throw the flute into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is coming up soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will then finally no longer make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
