The Sudets demanded a referendum from the United States.
The Sudeten Germans had asked for the integration of the Bohemian Forest into the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US president in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are entering German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter reads.
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia suggests that the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - would expect brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the Bohemian Forest as a guardian for now and forever.
“We cannot believe that, without regard to the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are addressing a foreign state to us, which is trying to oppress and eliminate minorities and has not contributed to the victory of the Allies at all,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president has doubts about the attitude of the Germans in the Bohemian Forest, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest on whether the inhabitants would become part of the United States or wish to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naïve in today's knowledge of post-war history, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, it paints a good picture with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even though the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that one would negotiate their deportation from the republic, only a few of them agreed to such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed as a Budweiser German in the Navy at the Baltic Sea during the war.
When he came to British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner of war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would come to them," Chalupa said.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
