Sleepless nights for Hypo Real Estate creditors
The German banking system is relatively stable, Federal Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück stressed only last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also interwoven that the German banking sector is not spared from the crisisful developments.
Because it happened this weekend.
The Munich-listed real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE) receives a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks in order to shield itself from the turbulence in the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan aid amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part that it also uses.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
The background is losses in the daughter Depfa.
According to a newspaper report, the state financier had refinanced himself extremely short-term for long-term projects for which he has loaned money - which is now no longer possible due to the mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s cash reserve had shrunk by 95 percent to EUR 2.37 million, while the equity ratio had also slightly declined from 1.6 percent to 1.45%.
Current earnings and net income from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, earnings from attributions to receivables and certain securities as well as from the dissolution of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher earnings from reimbursements of downstream settlement costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest under the Tax Code and from the business management for group companies, the earnings reduction had still been moderate at around 16 percent.
The former state financier had first speculated with commercial real estate loans after his privatization in 1990, which had then been outsourced to Aareal Bank.
Because they did not earn enough in the classic state financing, the Depfa had then become increasingly involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of joint projects of private investors and the state (Private Public Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter, the Hypo Real Estate must now make depreciations that will have a "substantial material effect" on the profit and loss account of the group, it is quite indefinite.
The fact is that the dividend has been canceled.
By 2007, it had been cut by two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure financier since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is more dependent than other institutions on refinancing in the interbank market because it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending among banks has again largely dried up as banks hoard their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term funds to be refinanced annually for part of Depfa’s loan portfolio – around EUR 50 billion.
According to the Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing needs are covered by the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is “shielded from the influence of the currently largely incapacitated international money markets”.
It can be heard from other sources that thanks to the funds, the refinancing is secured until the end of 2009.
HRE CEO Georg Funke said, on the other hand, that the Hypo Real Estate Group will no longer have to use the money markets in the foreseeable future.
Bundesbank and the Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht (BaFin) assume that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate Group is now secured.
This is hoped for shareholders and creditors of the bank.
But given the dynamics and uncertainties of the crisis, there is no certainty.
In fact, it is not unthinkable that the financing does not have to be fully utilized.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the bank was reportedly facing insolvency on late Sunday evening, the at least provisional rescue could not calm the minds.
The share price drops by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
On the other hand, bond prices are quite good.
While the priority debts are barely moving, the rates of the subordinated bonds drop more clearly.
The bonds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and, understandably, the maturities beyond 2009 are particularly affected.
If hypo-real-estate bonds were formerly a speculative investment alternative, their worthiness must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international financial system after the significant exacerbation of the banking crisis and of the institution itself, which had only come into being with the takeover of the Depfa.
As long as the central banks, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, a timely repayment of pensions can be assumed.
Or what hardly anyone dares to hope for right now is that the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
However, in view of the reports that are overlapping with the partial nationalization, the probability of security has now become only a legitimate hope.
This is especially likely to give long-term creditors some sleepless nights with the decision to separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can at least use a closing line to form a loss presentation for future payroll tax payments on price gains later years.
