On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever it may be, probably differs greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or analyzed on the basis of our own experience, because of the special hardware, his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more readily accessible scientifically.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the development of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I trace them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and in particular humans.
Linked to the linguistic nature, fine gradations of feeling result, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed very much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-gender sensations.
In theory, I cannot contradict this, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably also feels like this in both cases: But how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A scavenger flees in danger if she too feels fear?
In my view, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove experience equality.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, on the other hand, scrapes do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove this to people: How did you want to prove it to rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even scrapes (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is being made here at the neural level, provided that the same is measured in rats and humans.
As I do not research language and consciousness in rats, nor do I research sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You might think it's short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than running against a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
