Compared to its colorful neighborhood The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historical impression.
Some believe that the street got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was split between his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was claimed by none.
The back door of the CBGB music club, the punk rock monument, which closed in 2006, opened to the Extra Place and the street is certainly best known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia".
The pavement was great, said Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones, who had taken the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of scrap, rags and parts of barrels, posters, sheets and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that this public property, as modest as it is, should remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged city splitter that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's vanishing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Complaints: A Bitter Nostalgic Look at the Extinct City"), has published part of the talk of city history about Extra Place, which was published in The New Yorker magazine in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that even remains dark during the day and is marked by rusted metal doors of the warehouses, closed windows and week-old newspapers flying past rain gutters".
With a few exceptions, the street looked just like it was recently in one evening.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where today there is a more expensive clothing store.
Graffiti could be seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bunch of discarded newspapers.
Some passersby said they had rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that the road could be polished up a bit.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the charm of the road in their current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in places that were dark, damp, and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of the Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research associate in Caliphonic Studies and senior director in the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Selection".
Talking to Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the likelihood of successful completion of school among African-American and Hispanic students is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who first learn English.
Yet the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take "Sixth Street Prep", a primary school in eastern Los Angeles, for example.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one third of students, many of whom have recently been in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astounding 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved with other methods than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school practices the approach according to which the education runs in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point Obama is supposed to consider, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, one would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him anymore.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within its own party (the national imagery associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation aimed at “English only.”
Instead, he said, "You should make sure that your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than contempt and trivialize them.
Oil prices fall as a result of renewed fears about the economy
The oil price fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the American bailout plan for the financial markets could not suffice to revive the economy.
Crude oil futures trades on the New York Stock Exchange fell by 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel during the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has dropped by more than $20.
In the last two weeks, the goods markets have been shaken by both the financial turbulence on Wall Street and strong hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked at $145.29 per barrel in July, they fell to nearly $90 per barrel this month, then rose again as a result of the enormous uncertainty in the financial markets.
On Monday, investors have shown concern again, even though congressional representatives had announced they had agreed on a rescue plan this weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was still far from complete.
In the for now final chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government announcement on Monday, Citigroup is expected to buy up the bank operations of Wachovia Corporation.
In the meantime, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partly nationalized the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it appears that it has not succeeded in revitalizing the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to continue to decline.
Deutsche Bank analysts have written in a statement to investors that the forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe they continue to write that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of goods markets, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
The bank’s analysts have lowered their oil consumption expectations due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and their oil and gas price forecasts for 2009 have been reduced by 20%.
