Exhausted Gebrselassie beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why some consider him the best long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to reach the 42.2 kilometres in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the win on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has reached at least one world championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometre to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Olympic marathon in Beijing, out of fear, perhaps exaggerated in hindsight, that air pollution could worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in the sun and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie has won with an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya switched to long distances, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in Berlin in 1998 with the result 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and could not train for a week.
Obviously, he was refreshed after a break and did not return rusted.
"I'm so happy," he told reporters.
“Everything went perfectly.
I resumed the training a week ago and had some concerns today, but in the end it was all great."
He was criticized for – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s rival from East Africa – orchestrating his races excessively, avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars in general, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a rail race, and setting world records over the competition.
But this criticism hardly harms the size of Gebrselassies as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the centre of the track in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, have continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pacemakers had subsided.
Just over three miles ahead of the finish, Gebrselassie made his last appearance to separate from Kwambai, who arrived second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost 5 minutes.
