She missed the games in Beijing due to problems described as a back injury, but she recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She cleverly planned her run by having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners torn out first, but overtaken after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Tucked away between the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquettes, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writer’s Project at the time of the depression – remains in many ways a place of very special variety.
Eatonville is so independent, dignified and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth a resident of the city and a community member of the oldest church in the city.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the – sometimes condemned, sometimes praised – black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And really, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written by mouth, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through Florida’s often-forgotten center, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Like Oskar in real life as well as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and always fits in with hourly rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things the way they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to town, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable clothing style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he was swinging in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no major commemoration, no public readings on a grand scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main road of the community.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff on the people sitting away," Mr. Franklin said.
“There was once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to enforce integration by describing its decision in the Brown case against the school board as “offensive rather than respecting my race.”
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being embraced - I remember - hugging his teacher in the morning and hugging his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"They didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors, and artists who set themselves apart from prejudices, as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set off to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found in the bookshelves, and again made it a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came exactly at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many return every January for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway invigorated the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused genuine citizen pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
More and more people have come here, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals have begun to re-appreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (named Hurston of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: just 6 miles from Orlando city centre, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black today.)
Outsiders in search of Eatonville’s history and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, a permit is required in advance and certain things - such as the mural painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up like any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, the 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who, according to him, might need some help.
And even the younger ones, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Most people who just drive through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York we speak fluent financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
