Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-wing judge of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party of Austria, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, took part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008 to represent the organization "Cities Against Islamization".
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed with a red line.
The police are accusing right-wing extremists of the burial at a Muslim cemetery in Austria, on the same weekend at which extreme right-wing parties have made significant gains in the country’s parliamentary elections.
On the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun near Linz were severely damaged in an action organized, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols like the David Stern on some of the graves, but criminal officials consider this an attempt to obscure the motive of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the grave atrocity that took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan comes to an end.
At the same time, there is a round of conscience research in Austria after the country slipped to the right in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that received almost 30% of the votes, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law in their election campaign and some of their election slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, advocated a ban on headscarves and burqas, and even expressed his aversion to foodstuffs generally associated with Islam.
