Conversation - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and developing guidelines to prevent another catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee at the time whose goal was to develop a new system for the management of canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this order.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is in charge of Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the Quebec blood canning system, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was daunting.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and by working in this field over the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before proudly stressing that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary maintains that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998, tells us.
“And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we cited one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is evident in Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proved without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person became infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and you could not recognize it, has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV to occur via a blood can.
I believe that you can feel comfortable these days when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
<0x60>Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can enter the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We have to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary, before emphasizing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
“The demand is increasing because the population is ageing.
Because the treatments for fighting cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only includes 3% of Quebec's blood donors.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
With these 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
“Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood canned but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being intervened at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
<0x60>A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood reduction as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
