Letters - A dishonored country
Mr. Vic Toews, ex-'Justice' minister (what irony) in Harper's cabinet, was the one who last summer allowed himself to say about Louise Arbour that she was a 'shame' for Canada.
This woman, who has waged a never-ending struggle for justice and deserves all our admiration for covering her with shame, says as much about the people around the prime minister as about Stephen Parker himself.
We are dealing here with a government that, as the only one from all the countries concerned, has not brought home its compatriot captured in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that doesn’t even take into account that Omar Khadr was still a youth when the things that were being accused of him happened.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, breaks its word and makes a child soldier go wild under inhuman conditions.
The only one who is condescending to a judicial parody to assess the defendant’s guilt.
Let us remember that especially UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Association of Canadian Lawyers are pleading to bring Omar Khadr home so that he can get a fair trial in Canada.
It is precisely this government that closes its eyes to torture: she cares very little that a young adult will surely be mentally broken after so many years of torment.
We are not yet aware of this, but we are experiencing an insidious circumcision here of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", this word that Harper is constantly carrying in front of us like a flag, and that sounds so insignificant from his mouth.
