The shame, Mr. Toews, lies in this abandonment, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-General Director of Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company was seeking a libel lawsuit over six million against three authors and a small, mediocre publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge about the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the goldmine’s almost inexhaustible pockets.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, by the way, often to ruin the defenders in order to enforce a consensual regulation that silences the other side and also deter anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast to what is going on in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas and not through bats.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate through the newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams that could have brought light to this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a handshake.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the opinions of this public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice-President, this word encompasses only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand — or doesn’t want to understand — is that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which it demands that they stop using this term...).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and truth-finding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It totally denies the right to quote credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and how to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures that restrict these types of unjustified lawsuits.
Wall Street bailout: Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months still needs to be adopted by the two congressional chambers.
The main contents are: better control of MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure the repayment of the public funds used, new injunctions to limit the number of houses imprisoned due to payment arrears, as well as the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
American Finance Secretary Henry Paulson, the President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the representative of the Republicans present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective,” Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said in a statement.
"Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street price crisis," she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t, the trauma, chaos, and unrest in Americans’ daily lives will be enormous,” said Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had accelerated during the last two hours, out of fear of the impact that another failure would have had on the sentiment of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who did not participate in the negotiations until late, were more likely to be proponents of the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to hit them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama insisted on the addition of certain injunctions to the agreement, especially those to allow owners to keep their homes, and those that affect the salaries of the senior executives of the state-saved companies.
“If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain individuals, this is not something to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on American television channels.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: “I’d like to know the details first, but I hope so.
The principles I have read [show] that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to progress.
The option of doing nothing at all is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at using the money of taxpayers.
It comes 14 months after a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to further forms of more common bonds (PCAA), and eventually resulted in a freezing of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt to reach an agreement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain “toxic” assets of the societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, it is believed to escape the impasse.
To round off the viewpoints for everyone in Congress, a decree has also been added that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to recover its capital used.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington will receive shares in the supported companies, which will yield dividends in the event of profits, and which it can sell again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to stop the attachment proceedings concerning the apartments bound by the real estate loans covered by this plan, and also to set deadlines for repayment and compensation paid to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, more votes were raised yesterday against this plan, both on the part of the Republicans and the Democrats.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t understand us,” Republican Scott Garett, a member of the Chamber’s Finance Commission, told his voters.
“Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists in asking the taxpayers to cash in.”
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called the “Caucus of Skeptics,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred excellent economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: We ask Congress not to be put under pressure and carefully consider which path to take,” he said.
At the same time, we in Europe once again got proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which has been in great trouble since it lost €2 billion ($2.9 billion) in the crisis due to the high-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
“This is not a lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
To compensate, we have a right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what the savers and households appreciate, now that uncertain times are announcing themselves.”
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank in distress from the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bradford and Bringley, including over 41 billion ($75.5 billion) from real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy up the British bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government has had to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure eyes was his trump for a long time, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, sensibility and an obvious talent have also kept him away from a power position that gives birth to the truly terrible monsters.
But what a great endurance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from the consequences of lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the golden years he has been.
He was less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and for whom he was a kind of rival on the screen for a long time, more careful in his spectacle, certainly also fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the blast of dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often results in wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 as the son of a German Jew and a Hungarian-born mother.
From its European roots, one of the glorious faces of the American dream was to emerge.
Without excessive ego, extreme quality feature.
For in him, an entire country that was in love with the self-made man was reflected in the fighters who were wounded in the Pacific War in battle, who studied acting in Yale in the early 1950s and then visited the Actor's Studio in New York before he had success at the theatre, on television and soon in the cinema.
This man, who fought for civil rights, was also the driver who finished second in Mans's 1979 24-hour race, and also a sex symbol, although he had lived in a flagship relationship with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With it, the unknown facets of this mysterious, restrained, committed and overly sensitive star, whose mystery will never be solved completely, disappear.
A decent man, in the purest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman moved the cinema lovers to Taumel this weekend, while all his big roles were played on the dark screen of memories.
More than half a century of American film art in constant change passes with him.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) and the young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Tin Roof, which was filmed by Tennessee Williams in 1958, come to mind.
A much shorter past memory (1990) is awakened to his sensitive Mr. Bridge, who at his old age is disturbed by a wedding that did not fulfill all of her promises.
There have been so many Paul Newmans throughout history.
This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, re-recorded after his death and made the Newman popular in 1956.
This sympathetic ganove in the superb The Sting (The Clou), who was awarded the Oscar for Best Film in 1973.
As a bitter and vengeful billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
This face through time, that was it.
Still him.
In his CV, epochs unite.
The youth knows him mainly from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the little orthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
With a last role in 2003 as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes, the circle closed.
Unlike several movie legends who retired from the film world early enough, Newman was supposed to stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, its fortunes, its splendor, and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humor, as a living challenge to ‘underplaying’ when he judged his all-too-expressive achievements.
The métier was not always easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles only flew this way for a long time.
However, he rarely played Sunnyboys as outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, fissures or despair, with whose perfect portrayal he reflected his gliding and revolt.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown sides of his true sensitive sensibility.
His 1968 Rachel, Rachel (after the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence) starring his wife Joanne Woodward, drew a subtle portrait of women full of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott due to an overdose, dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of sensitivity and sadness to him.
During the flood of honors that went on over Newman yesterday, his close friend and former gunmate Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and in Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, “His presence has improved my life and this country.”
Generousness and joie de vivre were essential characteristics of the deceased actor.
Apart from his legendary career, a great advocate of civil rights, environmental protection and independent cinema, an opponent of the drift of Hollywood, is now going to die.
We probably often saw him standing with his foot in bowls full of vinaigrette, in sauces, pastries or other foods, and thought this was quite tasteless, although we still found it funny at first.
Nevertheless, the profits from his sales went to his foundation for children in need.
Instead of resting on his myth, Newman committed himself to the point of shooting.
He left his five daughters a letter with these sentences: “Your father was always and until the very end incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was an honor to be here.”
And for us, it was an honor to be able to pursue the lives of such an intelligent and generous American actor.
An exemplary citizen, in the narrowest and broadest sense.
