At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue what is being filed.
Neurologists and business researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people don't want to give up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overriding plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To underpin their thesis, the economists in the research group have also done research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was merely that the emphasis was on winning one, while the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to make higher bets than those in the control or the "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far justified the behaviours observed at auctions only with the joy of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travelers are advised to vaccinate against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-induced, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first held by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of these chronic liver inflammations caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
