As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Using brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which released the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke some sort of religious trance among the faithful, while selecting da Vinci’s image, because it was hardly distinguished from the other painting and felt as reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during this time, while watching either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that when they saw the Mother of God, they felt “safe” as if they were “cared for” and felt “peace and tranquillity.”
While viewing the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced with other strong-acting images by the atheists, one would only have to find the appropriate photo.
"We would have to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
