Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was unveiled in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in creating new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C car-driven biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of a laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the auto robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires at the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the robot could not react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And this has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the evasion can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the manoeuvrability of the tires.
While the bees here have endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the robot to rotate, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained, it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous manoeuvres, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB of memory.
It does not require gigabyte and megabyte heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan believes will be in production in the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
