Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to abroad and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the wealth of private households residing in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for governments: namely how to behave towards the families affected, which also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears economically global, while politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism thus seems to have fallen apart and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its dividing into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects to intervene in their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the United States is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that are not to be overvalued – under certain circumstances – to which otherwise no international organization and no market will probably be able to resort in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance recently associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, right now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered into a networked total realm, into a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, the intangible, that we must at once determine how our future will increasingly depend on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While these can all be transported from one place to the other in the world, they are still connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who possesses such a territory is advantageous to another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free territory.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short introduction.
Whoever says territory, who says government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deep-reaching and, in a sense, disturbing aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, all aimed at a whole class of managers in the Western countries.
