THE NEW YORK TIMES QUESTION: IS ITALY RASSICAL?
Italy, "the former country of emigrants has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", which are only received with reluctance.
This is what the New York Times is asking in a long article devoted entirely to the theme of racism in Italy, starting from the case of the young Burkina Faso-born Abdul William Guibre, who was murdered a month ago in Milan after stealing a pack of cookies.
The case bears witness to what the Times calls the "paradox of the North": the northern regions are those where "the most integration and job opportunities" exist, and yet "the highest degree of anti-immigration sentiments and the greatest support of the Lega North is recorded".
As a confirmation of the growing tension between Italians and immigrants, the Times refers to further episodes of intolerance from Milan, Rome, Parma, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
And not just this.
The new legislation introduced by the Lega against immigration and the faster expulsion of illegal immigrants is also cited as a sign of climate change in Italy.
A movement that the Pope and the President also underline: "Giorgio Napolitano asked the Pope at a meeting in the Quirinal for a cooperation between the Church and the State to combat racism."
Victims of high rents of up to 900 euros per room
The housing market for students has no crises.
According to the latest investigation by Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
“This phenomenon has already taken on very serious traits, so many students are losing their right to study because their families are not able to support them at this level,” says Sunia’s executive Laura Mariani, “in these cities, the high demand from the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also harmed the other residents.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorised sub-rentals.
For Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of the taxation.
On closer examination of the investigation, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping place in the Brianza district is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a sleeping place costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are for a bed of necessity, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only slightly lower are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>.
Only those who dodge in outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a place to sleep and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of rental to non-European students is more common, such as in Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents that are 25-30% above the average are demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This image by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means death in the long run for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
Affected are mostly historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you've traveled a piece of road full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who earned him the Oskar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago. It's the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the vast number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; this mine paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main culprit is the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first and foremost, the preservation of what already exists, because a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are ready to go to a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the missing budget for the fund of the trade association remains externally eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral standpoint that the government does not comply with existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be in need.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, because of the fears of the old cinemas, has decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the measures foreseen are tax concessions for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at lower parking fees.
"It's a gratifying initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Certainly, however, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
