When the energy emanates from the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a non-ferrous source of money covering over 70% of the planet’s surface, and only now do the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not by chance, these studies intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gasified, but now the environmental organizations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be met by the energies generated by the ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which in 2005 signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies in the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is examining these technologies,” said the spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
It is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being extracted by the United States in Alaska and that President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, then observers speak of an increasing interest.
Improved technologies.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned facilities of this type, which are only waiting for state approval, and some of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator due to the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest deserves the potential that lies in the tides right now.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
